{
  "texts": [
    "The 'T ' in 'T -BAO' suggests tense algebras, which are usually taken to be BAOs with two operators, one of which is the conjugate of the other (see, e.g., Jónsson and Tarski 1951, Def.",
    "1.11, Jónnson 1993, §4.7, Venema 2007, Prop.",
    "8.5), i.e., such that ♦ 1 x ∧ y = ⊥ iff x ∧ ♦ 2 y = ⊥, in which case ■ 1 and ♦ 2 form an adjoint pair as above: x ≤ ■ 1 y iff ♦ 2 x ≤ y.",
    "We use 'f i ' instead of some kind of diamond notation as a reminder that this f i need not be definable by a term from the signature of the BAO, as well as to suggest a connection between T -BAOs and the (quasi-)functional possibility frames of § 4.4, which will be made explicit in Theorems 5.6.4 and 5.17.2 below.The following is a well-known and useful fact.Fact 5.2 (T and V).",
    "Any T -BAO is a V-BAO, and any CV-BAO is a CT -BAO."
  ]
}